  "prompt": "What is creamy layer?",
  "response": "In the context of India's reservation system, the \"creamy layer\" refers to the more economically and socially advanced sections within the Other Backward Classes (OBC) category. Specifically:\n\n1. Definition:\n- Individuals from OBC communities who have achieved a certain level of economic and social advancement\n- People who have crossed a specified income threshold\n\n2. Key characteristics:\n- Higher income group within OBC category\n- Better socio-economic status\n- High-ranking government positions\n- Professional success\n\n3. Purpose of creamy layer concept:\n- Prevent well-off members of OBC from claiming reservation benefits\n- Ensure reservation benefits reach more disadvantaged sections\n- Promote social mobility and economic equality\n\n4. Criteria for determining creamy layer:\n- Annual family income\n- Professional status\n- Government service positions\n- Educational qualifications\n\n5. Current income limit:\n- As of 2021, the creamy layer income limit is \u20b98 lakhs per annum\n- Individuals earning above this limit are excluded from OBC reservation benefits\n\nThe creamy layer concept aims to make reservation policies more targeted and effective in addressing socio-economic disparities.",
